{"cursor":"5533","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n on Wall Street, the world's largest stock exchange per total market\n capitalization of its listed companies. ]] 'Market capitalization'\n (or 'market cap') is the total value of the issued shares of a publicly traded\n company; it is equal to the share price times the number of shares\n outstanding. As outstanding stock is\n bought and sold in public markets, capitalization could be used as a proxy for\n the public opinion of a company's net worth and is a determining factor in some\n forms of stock valuation.\n\nThe total capitalization of stock markets or economic regions may be compared to\nother economic indicators. The total market capitalization of all publicly\ntraded companies in the world was US$51.2 trillion in January\n2007 [http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSL2144839620070321 Global stock\nvalues top $50 trln: industry data] (Reuters) and rose as high as US$57.5\ntrillion in May 2008 [http://www.world-\nexchanges.org/WFE/home.asp?menu=395 WFE Report Generator including report for\nDomestic Market Capitalization 2008] (World Federation of Exchanges)\nbefore dropping below US$50 trillion in August 2008 and slightly above US$40\ntrillion in September 2008.\n","linknr":288,"url":"Market_Capitalization","recorded":1375090089,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Market_capitalization&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Market_capitalization&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Market_capitalization","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wik